"""Medium leetcode patterns — 20+ commonly-asked problems with worked solutions."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is the rotate image problem?','Rotate n×n matrix 90 degrees clockwise in place. Two-step: (1) transpose (swap matrix[i][j] with matrix[j][i] for i<j). (2) reverse each row. Both O(n²). Alternative: rotate layer-by-layer (4-way swap per group). Variant counter-clockwise: transpose + reverse columns.'),
    ('What is the spiral matrix problem?','Traverse n×m matrix in spiral order. Maintain four boundaries (top, bottom, left, right); walk top-row left→right, right-col top→bottom, bottom-row right→left, left-col bottom→top, then shrink boundaries inward. O(n*m).'),
    ('What is the set matrix zeros problem?','If cell is 0, set entire row + column to 0. In-place O(1) space trick: use first row + col as markers. Track if first row or col originally had a 0 (two flags), then iterate inner cells writing 0 to first row/col, second pass zeros based on markers, finally zero first row/col if needed.'),
    ('What is the search rotated sorted array problem?','Sorted array rotated at unknown pivot. Find target in O(log n). Modified binary search: at each mid, one half is guaranteed sorted (compare arr[mid] to arr[left] to decide which). Check if target in sorted half\'s range; recurse into that half, else the other. Classic pivot-search trick.'),
    ('What is the search 2D matrix problem?','Sorted matrix: each row sorted, first of row > last of prev row. Treat as 1D: binary search over n*m indices, convert idx → (i,j) via div/mod. O(log(nm)). Alternative (staircase search): start top-right, if too big go left, too small go down. O(n+m) but works on weaker condition (rows + cols both sorted independently).'),
    ('What is the merge intervals problem?','Given list of intervals, merge overlapping. Sort by start. Iterate, merging with last result if current.start ≤ result.end. O(n log n) from sort. Variants: insert interval into sorted list (linear scan), count meeting rooms needed (sweep line on start/end events).'),
    ('What is the meeting rooms II problem?','Min rooms needed for all meetings. Two-pointer on sorted starts + sorted ends. Walk start times; if next start ≥ earliest end, reuse room (advance end pointer); else need new room. Max rooms used at any time = answer. O(n log n). Equivalent: events sweep — +1 on start, -1 on end, sorted by time; track max running count.'),
    ('What is the jump game problem?','Array where a[i] = max jump length from i. Can you reach last index? Greedy: track max reachable so far; if i > max_reachable, false; update max_reachable = max(max_reachable, i + a[i]). O(n). Variant II: min jumps to reach end — track current jump end + next jump max, increment jumps when crossing boundary.'),
    ('What is the unique paths problem?','m×n grid, only right/down moves, count paths top-left to bottom-right. DP: paths[i][j] = paths[i-1][j] + paths[i][j-1]. O(mn) time + space. Math: C(m+n-2, m-1) — choose which moves are downs out of total. Variant with obstacles: 0 paths through blocked cells.'),
    ('What is the climbing stairs problem?','N stairs, take 1 or 2 at a time. How many distinct ways? Fibonacci sequence: f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2). Base: f(1)=1, f(2)=2. O(n) time O(1) space. Variant: variable step set {1,3,5} — sum DP over allowed step sizes.'),
    ('What is the house robber problem?','Pick non-adjacent houses, max sum. DP: rob[i] = max(rob[i-1], rob[i-2] + a[i]). Either skip current and take previous, or take current + best two-back. O(n) time O(1) space (rolling vars). Variant: circular street → solve twice (excluding first OR excluding last), take max.'),
    ('What is the coin change problem?','Min coins to make amount N. DP: dp[i] = 1 + min(dp[i-c] for c in coins if c ≤ i, dp[i-c]<inf), dp[0]=0. O(N*len(coins)). Variant: count ways (not min) — dp[i] += dp[i-c] for each coin (order matters: outer coins, inner amounts → combinations not permutations).'),
    ('What is the word search problem?','Grid of letters; find if a word exists as connected path. DFS from each cell matching word[0]; backtrack with visited marker; try 4 neighbors. Mark visited by overwriting then restoring. O(m*n*4^len(word)) worst.'),
    ('What is the number of islands problem?','Grid of 0/1; count connected components of 1s. DFS or BFS from each unvisited 1, marking visited; each launch = one island. O(m*n). Trick: modify input grid (set visited to 0) to save O(m*n) extra space. Union-find alternative: union adjacent 1 cells, count distinct roots.'),
    ('What is the kth smallest element in a BST?','In-order traversal of BST gives sorted order. Stop at kth element. O(h + k) with iterative in-order + stack. If BST is balanced + frequent kth queries: augment nodes with subtree size, do O(log n) per query via "smaller-subtree" recursion.'),
    ('What is the validate BST problem?','Check if tree is a valid BST. Recursive with (min, max) bounds passed down: each node\'s value must be in (min, max); left subtree gets (min, val), right gets (val, max). O(n). Common bug: just comparing parent — missed cases like right child smaller than ancestor.'),
    ('What is the construct tree from inorder + preorder?','Preorder root = first element. Find root in inorder → splits into left + right subtree inorders. Recursively build. O(n²) naive; O(n) with hashmap of value→index in inorder. Works because preorder gives roots top-down; inorder gives left-root-right ordering for splits.'),
    ('What is the implement queue using stacks problem?','Two stacks: in (push) + out (pop). To push: push to in. To pop: if out empty, transfer ALL from in (reverses order); pop from out. Amortized O(1) per op (each element moved at most once). Classic interview problem.'),
    ('What is the design LRU cache problem?','O(1) get + put with capacity. Use hash map (key → node) + doubly-linked list (order by recency). get: move to head. put: insert at head, evict tail if over capacity. Python: collections.OrderedDict has move_to_end which makes this trivial.'),
    ('What is the longest substring without repeating characters problem?','Sliding window. Two pointers L, R both at 0. Hash set of chars in window. Move R right, adding to set. If duplicate, move L right removing chars until duplicate gone. Track max window size. O(n) time O(min(n, alphabet)) space.'),
    ('What is the longest repeating character replacement problem?','Substring of all same char allowing K replacements; find max length. Sliding window with char counts. Window valid if (window_len - max_count) ≤ K (need to replace minority chars). Expand R; if invalid, advance L. Track max valid window. O(n).'),
    ('What is the group anagrams problem?','Group strings that are anagrams of each other. Use canonical form as key: sorted chars OR letter count tuple. Hash map: key → list of original strings. O(n * k log k) with sorted, O(n*k) with count tuple where k = max string length.'),
    ('What is the find duplicate number problem?','Array of n+1 ints in range 1..n; one duplicate. Find without modifying. Cycle detection (Floyd): treat array as linked list (a[i] is next index). Fast/slow pointers find cycle entry = the duplicate. O(n) time O(1) space. Other approaches use mutation (sort) or O(n) space (set).'),
    ('What is the daily temperatures problem?','For each day, days until warmer. Monotonic decreasing stack of indices. Pop while current temp > stack top temp; for each popped, answer[popped] = current_idx - popped. Push current. O(n) — each element pushed + popped once.'),
]
